This is one of the best opportunities and experiences for an officer. The officers spent four days planning the year, running workshops, working on leadership, and of course having a ton of fun. We are very excited for the upcoming year and everything they have planned.

shared_text:
Jesika Holloway
October 15, 2019 at 4:21 AM ·

October 15, 1969 a male FFA member from California moved to strike out the word male from the FFA constitution at the 42nd National FFA Convention in front of 12,675 members. By only a two vote margin, the motion was carried. Despite the initial motion defeat in 1964, 1966, and 1968, women were finally permitted to join the organization.

To the young man who stood before thousands to address the future of females within the organization despite the initial motion defeat, I thank you! To the brave females before us that paved the way for females such as myself to find a home within this organization, I cannot thank you enough!
text:
Jesika Holloway
October 15, 2019 at 4:21 AM ·

October 15, 1969 a male FFA member from California moved to strike out the word male from the FFA constitution at the 42nd National FFA Convention in front of 12,675 members. By only a two vote margin, the motion was carried. Despite the initial motion defeat in 1964, 1966, and 1968, women were finally permitted to join the organization.

To the young man who stood before thousands to address the future of females within the organization despite the initial motion defeat, I thank you! To the brave females before us that paved the way for females such as myself to find a home within this organization, I cannot thank you enough!

2019 fair is off to a great start! Today our three members with dairy heifers competed in the FFA showmanship and quality show.

2nd in class for quality

Bryleigh Widmier- 1st in class for quality
Reserve grand champion
Overall 1st year heifers.

Calling all FFA Members! If you have some time on Saturday the 29th, one our members could use your help. Raegan Fitzpatrick is working on raising money to go towards starting an Murtaugh FFA member hard ship fund. This fund would help members in need to go to competitions, buy jackets etc. To do this he is asking for help at the Fitzpatrick Farm day in Hazelton. This is an event for kids and families to enjoy and learn about agriculture.

So here is what he needs. FFA members to come volunteer from 9-3 on Saturday or any amount of time. Wear any FFA gear, shirts, hats etc. The details are on the 2nd picture. If you need a ride please contact Mr. Johnson or Mrs. Abby Fitzpatrick. Let's get out and help out with this awesome project!

post_text:
EXCITING NEW PROGRAM!

With the end of FFA week, we would like to kick off a new program to give people the opportunity to buy some student made items.

Here is how this new program will work. Each week (as long as time permits) we will post pictures of an item to be auctioned off.
We will post the size, who made it, minimum bid, and when bidding will close. This will be a sealed bid silent auction style. If you would like to place a bid, dm this page or email the bid to FFA@murtaugh.k12.id.us After the close of bidding, the winner will be notified and can pick up the item at the Ag Building the next day.

Our very first item was made by Cody Walton. It is 31"x 31". The minimum bid is $75. Bidding for this item will close Wednesday the 27th at 6:00pm.

Let us know if you have any questions. Thank you for all your support!

The soils team had a great day! They took 2nd in the South Magic Valley FFA District. With incredible individual placings as well.

Meagan Holbrook- 4th high individual
Chandler Jones- 6th high individual
Daniela Aguilar- 11th high individual
Janessa McConaha- 15th high individual

The soils CDE (career development event) requires participants to evaluate soil for farm ground and a home site. Looking at traits like soil texture, slope, permeablity etc.

Special congratulations to our two newest members, Chandler and Janessa for doing so well their first time.

These members have qualified for the state competition which will be October 10th in Burley.

post_text:
We had a great week at the University of Idaho, competing in the State Career Development Events!
AG Mechanics Team-
Garrett Berry was 4th place high individual in small engines, and 10th high individual in tool reconditioning.
Kolby McClure was 10 high individual in gas/Tig welding.

Milk Quality Team placed 11th in state
Makayla Powers was 27th high individual and Sandy Damian was 39th high individual out of over 120 participants.

We didn't quite make our goals but the FFA members worked hard and we know what needs to be fixed for next year.

post_text: Pictures from our second day of the Challis class trip. We got the opportunity to see sea bass and shrimp production. Hydroponic strawberries, a fodder plant system and the only organic food processing kitchen in Idaho. We also made a quick stop at craters of the moon. We have to give one more huge thank you to Brad Perkins, Marie Alcala, and Jack Anderson for being our tour guides, cooks, and chaperones. Incredible opportunities like this are not possible without great people like them.
